<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-797-380  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 797 380.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 27 1990 v24 n35 p59(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Data center automation; consolidation promotes hands-off strategy.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Feuche, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The consolidation of various data centers into super centers hascreated a need for automation tools.andP;  When Merrill Lynch andamp; Coconsolidated its seven data centers into two large facilities, thenumber of batch jobs run daily increased four times and each datacenter processed six million on-line transactions a day.andO;Automation tools helped management gain control over the vastamounts of processing.andP;  Since super centers usually have tightprocessing schedules and are in operation around the clock, sevendays a week, automation tools are close to being a necessity.andO;Automated systems regarded as critical to managing data centersare tape management, job scheduling and balancing systems, andconsole automation tools.andP;  The tools enable staff reductions,allow operations to be managed remotely, and make data centeroperations more cost-efficient.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information CentersCentralizationAutomationOn-line transaction processingCost of OperationCost Benefit Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographgraph.andO;Caption:   Data center tasks that are most difficult and least difficult toautomate. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>